description.text: The NDS Lite is a great little machine but now it's hard to find working batteries for this thing. You go online to buy a battery advertised as 800mah but it comes as 400mah because it's been sitting in the warehouse for 5 years. Well forget that, just hack in a fresh 2400mah 18650 battery instead! It's still lithium so it recharges with the original recharging cable too.

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

15%

Notes:

Designed for PETG for its flexability and good layer adhesion - my material of choice.

Assembly
  1. Solder 2 pieces of wire about 5-10cm, each with a small spring on one end and a small strip of copper on the other.
  2. Wrap the strip of copper on the fake battery and glue it on the backside so the NDS's contacts can touch them when the battery is inserted.
  3. Insert the fake battery and leave the wires passing through its central hole. Secure the wires onto the fake battery with glue gun or your adhesive of choice.
  4. Remove the securing screw from the original lid and transfer it over to the new lid.
  5. Install the new lid, using the screw to secure the new lid just like the original.
  6. Insert the 18650 cell into the battery bay (cyltop) with the sprint contacts in the correct orientation. Note that the + terminal is closer to the back of the NDS so ensure this terminal is connected to the + of the battery.
  7. Squish the excess wire into the battery bay and install the small battery lid (cylbotlid).
  8. Mate the battery bay to the protruding fake battery and insert the M2 screws to secure.

Tools used:

Fusion 360, vernier Calipers, cell phone camera, sheer autistic perfectionism

Non printed ingredients

1x PROTECTED 18650 cell, usu. for flashlights.
2x copper strips for interfacing the battery contacts in the NDS
2x wire
2x spring for interfacing the 18650 cell
1x original securing screw from the NDS battery bay lid
2x 4mm M2 Screw

Ensure that...

... the 18650 cell is protected, i.e. has overvoltage and undervoltage protection, not flat top raw cells.
... the M2 screws are not long enough to scratch the 18650 cell when installed. Shorter than 5mm is fine.
... the polarity of the battery is correct when installing, or you could damage your NDS lite.

description.text:
I modified the end cap for the Mean Well SE-450-24 power supply for my Taz 4.
(p/s= power supply))
This mod uses parts from an old PC ATX power supply, namely the press in switch and 3 pin male AC socket. The 24VDC output hole uses a used Taz 4 DC power cable which was de-soldered from a stock power supply I was not using. This requires lengthening wires, and cutting the wire between the switch and socket and then reconnecting them after they are installed in the cover. I added forked terminals, crimped and soldered to attach to the p/s teminals.
If you want to temporarily remove the pins from the end of the connector that plugs into the Taz electronics, you can install the cable from the inside of the p/s cover and not have to use screws to retain it. I used the screws from the outside and had to drill two holes in the rubber flange. Not pretty or easy, but strong.
I would have preferred to modify the cap a bit more because I felt it was a bit too wide and caused undue stress after installing the M4 screws to hold it on the p/s. I used PLA and was concerned that it might crack, but it did not, and does not look like the added stress to the mounting flanges will be an issue. If I was to re-design I would remove a couple of mm from the width of the cover to make it fit closer the the power supply.
I used PLA at 205C/70C fan after layer two. I had made two covers out of ABS and both pulled off the bed or split in the lower layers, so I switched to PLA. I used no support and rotated to print with the connector and switch holes on the bed.
There are 2 .stl files. One is 5mm thick (that's the one I used. I had also designed it as 3.5mm thick, but did not try it as I started with the 5mm version and did not want to dismantle it. The 3.5 mm thick version should work fine if you want to try it. Again, I would rotate it to print with the connector socket and switch holes against the bed to avoid having to use supports.
You will need 4 M4 x 10 machine screws to mount it, 2 M3x 12 screws and nuts for the AC jack, and 2 M3 x 20mm screws and nuts it you mount the DC cable from the outside. If you mount the DC cable from the inside by temporarily removing the DC pins, I would add a zip-tie to the stress relief on the outside as it leaves the hole. Use some washers against the plastic. So, 4 3mm washers and 4 4mm washers.
note: in the photo of the finished p/s I only had two short cap screws, so the upper screw has a nut on it to prevent it from protruding too far into the p/s until I can get a couple more short M4 screws.
I have a lot more faith in this power supply than the stock one, and supposedly the higher DC output rating is supposed to help. So far so good. Just the power switch alone is a nice improvement.

Update 10/13/2017: I added some feet so I could stand this power supply vertically to minimize ths chance opf something falling in the venting and fan holes. See photo above.

description.text:
This is a replacement knob for a ceiling fan, attic fan, or the shrouds of those fans. It fits on to a wall-plate-mounted rotary switch, similar to that of a light switch, but instead of a light switch there's a rotating head.

It fits on to mine, at least. I'm not sure if there's a standard size for this sort of item, or if mine's just proprietary. Here, why don't you go measure yours first?

The shape of the rotating axle should be like a circle truncated on two parallel sides. The circle diameter should be roughly 6mm and the distance between either truncated end to the other should be about 5.25mm, give or take a little. It is a press fit, so it won't matter much if it's off by about 0.05mm or so.

Hope this model can save someone some work!

title: Slide Top Rabbet Box (Customizer for 3D Printers and CNC)

description.text:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nRACN7DZ0nI

I created this box generator because I wanted a design suitable for both 3D printers and CNC machines. This generator produces boxes with rabbet joints at the edges which provide precise alignment during glue up. This box design also features a sliding lid. For CNC users, this box can be fabricated by cutting from one side and requires little to no finishing work.

Here are a few tips to using the generator...

The box dimensions are in millimeters and define the outside measurements of the box. If you have size requirements for the inside, you will need to account for the wall thickness.

The tolerance slider controls the looseness of the lid fit. It is a numeric value representing a percentage of the material thickness. The default tolerance of 4 percent for a box with 8mm thick walls would produce a lid tolerance of 0.32mm. You can slide the tolerance down to zero, but it is likely that your lid flange will not fit in the slot without some sanding. The tollerance for the lid is achieved by making the receiving slot for the lid wider rather than by making the lid flange thinner. This maintains a uniform cutting depth for CNC users.

The bit value controls the spacing between pieces in the layout. If using a CNC, the bit value should be larger than the diameter of the cutting tool.

I usually use the default layout. Other layouts are not gauranteed to work. However, you should experiment with the different layouts because in certain box configurations the other layouts may fit the build area better.

For CNC work I usually use a 3mm flat endmill. It is important that the cutting tool be smaller than half the material thickness or else the slots for the lid cannot be cut. This box generator produes .STL output which needs further processing through a CAM program to produce the CNC cut paths. I use Vectric products for this, but other CNC CAM programs will work as well.

description.text:
Tired of the puny, wimpy blower fan on your Anet A8 / AM8? Hold on to your horses, 'cause this bracket will let two 80mm fans pick up all the slack.

This bracket replaces the tiny, worthless blower fan that comes with the Anet A8 stock, and uses the same two screws that used to hold that stupid waste of space in place.

All you need are two regular 80mm PC fans. How you decide to power and switch them is up to you - I personally wire them to my 12v power supply with a switch mounted to the front of the AM8 chassis, and just turn them on once the first layer is done printing.

The STL file is upside down and rotated to fit on the Anet build plate, taking up 172.2 x 172.2 x 58.9mm of space. I used supports (Cura setting "touching buildplate" with an angle of 50 degrees) and printed it with a 5mm brim for bed adhesion.

Edit:

  • Flattened the top of the fan brackets to allow for better bed adhesion.
  • Elongated mounting holes to allow for 5mm of vertical adjustment.
  • Trimmed extraneous edges around the center bracket.
  • Lengthened bracing along the edges of the fan brackets.
  • Thickened fan mounting plate edges
  • Enlarged fan mounting holes
  • Added fourth (smaller) fan mounting hole to use one of the long 3x30mm screws from the stock Anet kit to secure that corner, sized for self tapping - mostly to keep that corner from vibrating against the bracket.

description.text:
This is a proof-of-concept for a lower-friction printed bushing. In contrast to conventional printed bushings, only 10 mm of the SCA bushing's total length makes direct contact with the rod. This makes the SCA bushing more tolerant of misaligned linear rods.

The photos uploaded with this Thing contain three sets of graphs, showing the acceleration of the build platform (in mm/s^2) when the bed is being moved back and forth along the Y axis by a gcode script. The pla_tightened graph has conventional PLA bushings installed. The sca_bushing graph has SCA bushings installed. steel_bearings has factory steel LM8UUs installed.

For SCA bushings, the overall peak height, the difference between the troughs and peaks, and the steepness of the acceleration slope are all reduced compared to conventional bushings.

When compared to steel bearings, the SCA bushings take more oomph to start them moving (i.e. the troughs are all higher), but the steel bearings also caused the build platform to vibrate a lot more in the Z direction, which is why I designed these SCA bushings in the first place.

This design worked well for me, although it still had the same stiction problem that all printed bearings have, even when the inside was coated with dry PTFE. Perhaps graphite powder will perform better.

These bushings will wear out faster than normal full-length bushings, but it is trivial to print more.

It works as I made and have been using short bushings (even nuts) using Igus filament for more than a year. The load on these 3D printer is light and no need for the full size bearings. OD Diam can be reduced too.
Less friction and saves on weight and material. No play either when properly made and reamed. Burnishing, heat can be used to improve the finish, align bushings ...
But PLA is not the right material, lubrication will help but the whole point of these bearings is to avoid any kind of lubrication.

description.text:
After attempting to print Part 3 of this: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1308002 multiple times and failing despite doing everything that was recommended in the comments, I decided to roll up my sleeves and try to repair the problems in the model.

One problem I encountered with multiple failed prints was the lack of permanent supports on the side pylon pieces. I added some as an attachment to the barrel in the center, which while it may add a little more to the print time, are well-hidden from the casual eye and make it a lot easier to align and mate the different parts during assembly.

Please note that I am not a 3D god and do not purport to know every single trick to making a wholly optimized model for 3D printing. I only tried to get it to a sliceable and printable state, while also doing some cleanup. title: Spinning Witches Key FOB

description.text:
Every 'Witch' needs this key FOB for their Broomstick keys... a fun talking point over the Halloween period but will also be appreciated by Witches all year round!

Like most Key FOB's this is purely a fun, decorative accessory. The design features a Witch on her Broomstick in the centre of a rotating / spinning ring. The Witch and outer surfaces are raised so you can have fun making it in two colors by pausing your machine mid-print (twice) and swapping the filament... this is easy to do and creates a great result.

The mid section starts at 2mm build height and is 1.5mm thick... so swap filament at approx. the following build heights:

First color change: Change at 1.5 - 1.8mm completed (before the centre section starts to build by bridging between the witch and the outer rings).

Second color change: Swap the filament back as soon as you see the witch shape appearing above the centre bridged surface. Change at approx. 3.8 - 4.0mm completed.

For members with a dual extruder machine split files have been added for ease of printing the Witch FOB in two colors. Part A will print the bottom 1.8mm and from 3.8mm to completion. Part B will print the 2mm in between.

This is a small (34mm diameter at standard scale), quick and easy print that uses very little filament (7gm with a Raft). They make great gifts and can be printed to suit any Witches favourite colors.

A well sliced file printed on a precise / accurate machine should result in a FOB with a centre section that will rotate with minimal effort required to free it up. Running a finger nail or craft knife around the groove between the inner and outer parts (refer images) is all that should be required. Applying a light (silicone) lubricant in this area will help it rotate well.

However, if your FOB won't rotate and you can't free it up, you can scale it up uniformly (5-10%) to increase the designed in clearances.

Print one / some today to stay onside with the Witches in your household / life or risk having a spell cast upon you! (...and please post images of your Spinning Witches Key Fob's for other members to see).

Refer to the images and print setting for additional information / recommendations.

Note: If you like this check out the rest of my practical and fun designs.

A few quick things to do...

You will need to break the centre section free so it will rotate. A well sliced file printed on an accurate / precise machine should break free with minimal effort. Other machines may require a bit more time (refer to images).

title: Pattaya3D - Full 3D printed RC sailplane/glider (aliante) - original design by Franck Aguerre
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
Come iniziare? Ringraziando l'autore originale dell'aeromodello: Franck Aguerre, che lo pubblicò su una rivista francese una decida di anni fa', ovviamente da costruire in balsa :) Ho cercato di ridisegnarlo il più fedelmente possibile, con gli accorgimenti necessari per renderlo "stampabile 3d".

Questo progetto mi ha entusiasmato come poche altre cose ultimamente e il risultato per me è eccellente, sono molto contento! Il primo volo (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=geXliPhpYvI) è stato un successo: il Pattaya ha volato ed è anche tornato a casa tutto intero, quasi incredibile :) E farlo volare è un piacere (https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rr-XVDYDp7E)

Per invogliarvi a stamparlo posso dirvi che con 20/30 ore di stampa (senza supporti!) riuscite a fare tutti i pezzi e che con pochissimo altro lavoro l'aereo è pronto al volo. Anche gli accessori extra necessari sono pochi: due servi, una baionetta e due fili di acciaio!

Il Pattaya vola molto bene ed è medio/veloce; le dimensioni non sono eccessive: 85cm di apertura alare, ma è comunque molto stabile. Nasce come aliante ma anche la versione motorizzata ha il suo perché! (non credevo).
<iframe allowfullscreen="None" frameborder="0" src="https://www.youtube.com/embed/geXliPhpYvI" ></iframe>

• 200 gr di PLA
  • 2 x servi 5gr: http://goo.gl/EzTDbf (disponibile anche l'STL per i più comuni servi da 9gr: ora testati, sembrano ok)
  • 1 x baionetta da 3mm x 20cm (in beta anche l'STL per usare baionetta da 4mm)
  • 2 x fili di acciaio da 1mm (per i comandi dell'ala, vedi foto)
  • 2 x tubicini: 1mm diametro interno x 2mm diametro esterno (per i comandi dell'ala, vedi foto)
  • OPZIONALE: Al posto dei fili e dei tubicini sopra riportati è possibile usare una barretta di acciaio da 2mm, da infilare direttamente nell'ala e da piegare per fare il comando, da infilare poi nel servo allargando sicuramente il foro (non facilissimo).
  • OPZIONALI: 2/4 calamite, oppure benissimo del nastro telato come da foto per tenere insieme le ali
  • colle: attak (cianoacrilato) e/o bicomponente
  • ricevente e batteria
  • FINE!

Peso in ordine di volo (versione glider): 250/300gr
Peso in ordine di volo (versione motorizzata): 300/350gr
Apertura alare: 83cm
Lunghezza: 53cm
Profilo alare: fad05 (https://tracfoil.com/airfoils/index.php?page=fr_f)

Profilo dell'ala con comando Aggancio al servo

Indicazioni generali

La stampa è la parte più delicata di questo progetto, bisogna giocare col compromesso peso/robustezza.
Vi indicherò percentuali di infill, numero di layer, ma soprattutto un range di peso ottimale (comunque indicativo). Dalla mia esperienza in base al peso stimato dal software si può giocare con l'infill per migliorare la struttura interna della parti, a parità di peso, cambiando inclinazione e motivo dell'infill e altri parametri, diversi da software a software.

Ho stampato con nozzle da 0.3mm e da 0.4mm, il risultato è molto simile.
Altezza del layer: 0.2mm per tutte le parti.

Il timelapse della stampa può aiutare a capire come posizionare le parti per la stampa: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=kYcKbTu28WA

Le ali: 1-5% infill, 1 layer perimetro, 2/3 layer bottom, 2 layer top

Ogni semiala deve pesare dai 55gr ai 65gr l'una ed è formata da due pezzi alti 20cm ciascuno.
I due pezzi vengono stampati in verticale a crescere ed incollati col cianoacrilato (attack) che per questo utilizzo è perfetto. Attenzione che appena i due pezzi sono messi a contatto non si muovo più, essendo la superficie liscia.
Cercate di far cadere l'infill intorno al foro della baionetta, sarà più robusto.
Per fare la seconda semiala bisogna specchiare sull'asse X o Y lo stesso file.
E' possibile stampare i 2 pezzi insieme, o anche tutti e 4.

la coda: 1-5% infill, 1 layer perimetro, 2/3 layer bottom, 2 layer top

La coda è formata da due pezzi: la vera coda (15/20gr) e il raccordo col corpo (15/20gr)
Stampati in verticale a crescere e incollati con attack o bicomponente, stesse indicazioni delle ali.
Il raccordo può avere internamente una croce come infill, mentre la coda è possibile stamparla a 0% di infill con un layer orizzontale ogni 20/50 livelli (alcuni software lo consentono).

La leggerezza della coda è più importante che in altri pezzi, perché evita di dover mettere peso in punta, purtroppo però è anche il pezzo più delicato in atterraggio: poco male, al massimo si ristampa!

Il corpo: stampa "orizzontale", 15% infill, 1/2 layer perimetro, 2 layer bottom, 2 layer top

Il copro è formato da due pezzi ad incastro (quindi sono due file diversi, non si può specchiare il pezzo). Sono da incollare insieme dopo aver incollato i servi negli appositi incastri.
Ogni pezzo deve pesare dai 20gr ai 25gr l'uno e la stampa è orizzontale, al contrario di tutti gli altri pezzi. L'incollaggio delle due parti ad incastro consiglio di farlo con la bicomponente.

Corpo ad incastro Il "naso" (dai che è fatta!): 20%(0%) infill, 3 layer perimetro, 3 layer bottom, 3 layer top

Il naso è presente in due versioni: svuotato e pieno.
Il naso svuotato è utile per aggiungerci peso, di base è di 5/8gr ma è da portare ad almeno 20/30gr per un corretto bilanciamento del modello.
All'inizio lo attacco col biadesivo per poterlo cambiare facilmente per bilanciare l'aereo correttamente: vedere la sezione "Volare".

nasi :)

Siete pronti al volo?
Questo è il manuale del Pattaya "originale" di Aguerre: https://www.topmodel.fr/goodsdoc/100004_time_1323948728.pdf
Trovate indicazioni utili per i settaggi e varie info, l'aereo è molto simile, ma in ogni caso riassumo due cosine:

  • La configurazioni delle ali è "Integrale", sia la virata che il beccheggio vengono fatti muovendo interamente le ali con dei mix sulla radio, l'illustrazione qui sotto illustra meglio di tante parole. Usate esponenziale abbastanza marcato, 50% per il rollio (virata).
  • Il bilanciamento: per farla breve, tanto farla lunga è inutile :): due dita sotto le ali all'altezza dei buchi delle calamite del corpo, qui deve picchiare leggermente (in ordine di volo ovviamente) e poi regolatevi dopo i primi test di volo con la posizione di batteria e ricevente.

Video motorized version: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Btz9mCOTfdM

Non ero per motorizzarlo: poi abbiamo regalato una stampante 3D a Dario, il mio istruttore aeromodellistico, che ha pensato bene di ricambiare con una stampa di tutti i pezzi di un Pattaya3D. E quindi con un modello in mano già fatto, non ho resistito.
Il risultato è stato eccellente, volo perfetto e nessun contro o quasi!

  • Motore: Turnigy 2205 2300kv, agganciato al posto del naso con 4 viti (vedi foto)
  • Esc: 20A
  • Elica: richiudibile 6x3
  • Batteria: 3s 850mah
Motoried version - fly test!

Questo progetto è in evoluzione: se vi lanciate nella realizzazione, se trovate errori, se volete modifiche scrivetemi!
Mi piacerebbe molto vederlo realizzato da qualcun'altro di "sconosciuto" :)

Info

Hi, I don't have time and skill to translate all the descriptions in english, but I try do a little summary with basic information that I think can allow printing and flight!

Printing

for wing, tail and "rear" body: VERTICAL printing, 1-5% infill, 1 layer perimeter, 2/3 layer bottom, 2 layer top.
wings: 2+2 parts, each single wing must weigh from 55 grams to 65 grams
tail+junction (rear body): 2 parts, 15/20grams + 15/20grams

for the "front" body: horizontal printing, 15% infill, 1/2 layer perimeter, 2 layer bottom, 2 layer top
2 parts, 20/25 grams each.

Fly

This is the french manual of original "Pattaya", many information:
https://www.topmodel.fr/goodsdoc/100004_time_1323948728.pdf

Good flights!

description.text:
I had been searching for a nice way of attatching a suppressor to my crosman 1377 without having to buy a longer barrel. I couldn't find anything on the internet that I liked, so I came up with something myself.
This suppressor works way better than I had ever expected. The only thing I hear is the sound of the hammer hitting the valve. Now I can comfortably shoot it outside whithout having to worry about my neighbours.
And the total cost is less than $5,-.

Make sure to post the results when you made one for yourself.

Printer:

Da Vinci Mini

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Infill:

90%

Notes:

Make the prints SOLID (90% infill to compensate for the 0.4 mm nozzle).
Chose strength over looks!
The suppressor MUST NOT BE printed with supports!
The barrel band MUST BE printed with supports!
You will need around 30 m of plastic for the entire project.

Post-Printing work on the suppressor:

After the suppressor is printed, true up the inner holes with a 5.0 mm drillbit.
Drill three equally spaced 5.0 mm holes where the suppressor will go around the barrel band.
Thread these holes for a m6 bolt. I used those little bolts that are used to attatch the doorhandle to its frame (see img).

Post-Printing work on the barrel band:

Once the barrel band is printed, the hole in the barrel extension must be trued up with a 6.0 mm drillbit. Then true up the hole that goes around the point of the barrel with a 8.0 mm drillbit. This hole locks the barrel in place, so take your time. The hole were the barrel itself is slid into, should fit without any help of a drillbit. If this is not the case for you, then use some sandpaper or a 11.5 mm drillbit.

To make the suppressor and the barrel band fit nicely together, you will have to follow these steps:

  1. Glue an o-ring to the front of the barrel extension. This will make sure the air cant escape.
  2. Put some gastape around the barrel extension, so that the suppressor fits snugly and airtight around the barrel extension.
  3. Tighten the m6 bolts to secure the suppressor in its place. You could add some drups of superglue to make a more permanent fit.
  4. Use a 4.8/5.0 mm rod to align all the holes.

title: 5 & 6 Inch Ducts for Tricopter Mini / Baby, (Fusion 360)

description.text:
Note: I can take requests if someone requires something more specific. Please use the comments to list what you need as well as the dimensions and other relevant data.

5" (127 mm) Duct for RCexplorer mini / baby Tricopter (https://rcexplorer.se/)

For use with 5" Bull nose propellers, HQ 5x4x3 are ideal as I can get gap tolerances < 0.5 mm. Stiff propellers are best to prevent flexing during flight.

Motor mount modeled for the Emax RS2205kv motor but should work fine with motors of similar size.

Motor mounts can be found here: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2577985

Suggest low density, high stiffness print materials to create a duct as light as possible. Most "carbon fiber" composites or "SLS" Nylon (1.14D) is ideal. Keep in mind that the material Density varies from each mfr and process used. IMO "SLS" Nylon (PA or HP-PA) is BEST as it's strong, flexible and relatively cheap to print in comparison to Carbon. Avoid PETG, PLA and ABS as they're just too fragile and tend to separate / warp easily at the layer boundaries. Warping / Separation becomes a huge problem when printing the 6" Ducts due to the duct size and amount of support bracing required.

(10/7/2017): Added a stronger but heavier 5" version for those needing something more. Also added better fitting mounting holes for those using a Tricopter.

(10/9/2017): Added a 6" version with reinforced ribs / supports, while making the aero-lip hollow to save weight.

(10/17/2017): Added 6" version (8) with lift generating supports, both Clockwise (CW) and Counterclockwise (CCW) files have been included depending on your needs.

(11/6/2017) Added version designed for use with T-motor F80, features better supports and winglets.

(11/9/2017) Added a version for T-motor F80's that's without the side supports. Should be a bit easier to print. Was able to have a test print of these made out of ABS. Unfortunately the print quality was pretty bad and had excessive warping. Hence I was unable to test out the effect of the winglets.

Hand sanding for a proper finishing but do NOT paint. Painting adds weight and is often uneven, which can cause problems later on.

Shim the props, then tighten down the motor screws to ensure that the prop spacing is even.
Use pieces of cardboard or thick paper as shims that are exactly 0.5 mm thick (verifiy with micrometer). Be aware that cardboard does give a little so odds are the props end up closer to 0.3 or 0.4 mm. If done correctly, the shims shouldn't fall out while the motor mount is torqued down. (Use a cross pattern to tighten screws).

Note: Verify prop spacing before flight by spinning them by hand. Its possible (but rare) for the mounts to shift during transport or a hard landing. Trust me, you don't want the props contacting the ducts midflight.

Tricopter-Mini with Ducts (Video made by my 6-year old son, Erik) If the video fails to run, just open it on Youtube directly.
Fusion 360 / Sketchup
Special thanks to "Jan" and "Litterbug" for their help and advice throughout this project.

Did some efficiency testing today (10-11-2017) and came up with the following values

8.2 Amps @ Hover, HQProp 5x4x3 with 5″ Duct (Version-7), Flight weight approximately 720 grams

8.2 Amp @ Hover, HQProp 5x4x3 without duct, Flight weight approximately 606 grams

7.2-7.3 Amps @ Hover, Gemfan 6x4x3 without duct, Flight weight approximately 608 grams

7.1-7.2 Amps @ Hover, HQProp 6×4.5×3 without duct, Flight weight approximately 607 grams

20-Nov-2017: Flew a set of Master Air Screw props (6×4.5x3BN) and they’re fantastic. Was able to hover with just 6.2 Amps combined current draw. (F80-1900kv motors) By far the best propellers I’ve tried this far.

Note: Values taken from OSD and control rates turned down to allow for more sensitivity over throttle position. Amp draw is the total sum of all attached electronics and motors.

From the values shown above, it seems that the Ducts are making enough extra thrust to counteract their own weight. (114 Grams for all three) Furthermore, the larger prop sizes do indeed have higher efficiency. It stands to reason that when a 6″ Duct (Version-7) is used, the ducts should produce more than their own weight in extra thrust. This is due to the larger ducts “lip” surface area and reduced tip vortices from greater prop tip area in contact with the ducts inner wall.

Beyond this, I can definitely feel the difference with the ducts on and off. The ducts add a bit of automatic stability, making flying smoother and response time slightly slower. Overall I think this makes the tricopter easier and safer to fly. Unfortunately, installing the ducts correctly is rather difficult and time consuming.

Now as for the props used, “Stiff” Three bladed props are absolutely the way to go. Granted the two bladed props are more efficient but the craft feels loose / sloppy. I found that landing / hovering to be quite difficult with the HQprop 6×4.5×2’s. Another thing of note is that the Bullnose prop’s really do make a huge difference as they’ve a larger surface area that’s in close contact with the duct’s inner wall. (<1mm gap) Tried the Racekraft 5x4x3’s and found that the current draw was 1.5 Amps higher as the props edge facing the ducts wall was much smaller than the HQ 5x4x3's.

description.text:
I am still tinkering with the design but this one works really well. I will probably tweak the part cooling portion again (maybe switch to 40/50 mm fan) but for now it uses a spare 5015 fan I had laying around.

Whats Required:

  • Titan Aero
  • EzABL (optional) : The EzABL mount is very close to flush with other parts of the mount so people don't have to use it and instead can use normal size stepper (untested but should work).

description.text: This stackable organiser protects your optical fibres from accidental damage and over-bending and is inherently scalable to large arrays of fibres. The "base" piece has a mounting feature for an M6 caphead screw to mount to an optical table. You can then print as many "middle" pieces as you need to house all of your fibres then top it all off with a "lid" piece.

The inner diameter of the channel is 10 cm in order that it is impossible to bend the fibre below the usual minimum bend radius of 5 cm. Each piece can hold around 3x 0.9 mm diameter fibres of 3 m in length before things get a bit tight. Print a "base" piece and mount this to your optical table with an M6 caphead screw then print as many "middle" pieces as you need to house all of your fibres then top it all off with a "lid" piece. It is best to place the pieces on the table then arrange the fibres in them before adding further "middle" pieces or the "lid". We found that printing these with a lot of perimeters (we used 5) helps with the fairly thin walls. It also helped with adhesion when we printed onto fresh blue painters tape - this is quite crucial as you need these quite large pieces to come out with very flat bases.

description.text:
NOTE: I have not tested this version of this clamp yet. Expect an update with real pictures and possibly some fixes by Wednesday at the latest.

Edit: Photos are now posted, and Mk2.5 is now confirmed to work.

This thing is a system designed to clamp around the bell of a clarinet and hold a microphone for performance or recording. It was designed from scratch by myself, and it will be continuously updated probably until the end of 2017. I don't know if there is a standard size for clarinet bells, but if not, you can easily edit the design in Onshape, where the CAD files are publicly hosted, allowing you to change it as you wish.

On one side of the two piece clamp is a hinge, which is held together by n M3x15mm screw and nut. The other is a tool less latch which holds the clamp together using a M3x(>20)mm screw, two M3 nuts, and a spring from a regular old pen. The piece that holds the microphone is separate, which allows the whole clamp to be stored in a more compact way. This extra piece is held in place using integrated threads on the insert itself as well as one of the two clamp pieces. this setup allows for the microphone to face either up or down, as well as being securely attached. The microphone itself is suspended inside of the insert using small elastic bands for vibration dampening. these bands can be anything, but I used dental elastic bands used for braces.

The clarinet that I made this model for has a bell with an outer diameter of just over 70mm. If yours is different, or you want to modify it in some other way, you can find the document for this design on Onshape here.

This is my first functional design, so let me know how I did! If there's anything I can improve on, be sure to leave a comment about it. I love to get better at this stuff, and any tips on that help a lot.

  • 1x Clamp_1_MkX-X
  • 1x Clamp_2_MkX-X
  • 1x Mic_Insert_MkX-X
    Which version should I use?
    For each of your parts, the version number (MkX-X) should be the same, ideally being the largest number of all available versions (where MkX-X translates to version X.X).

    Hardware

  • 1x M3x15mm bolt, flat or button head
  • 1x M3x20-30mm bolt depending on the length of your spring
  • 3x M3 nut
  • 2x small elastic bands--dental elastics work great
Assembly

The hinge uses the M3x15mm screw and one M3 nut. Clamp_2 has a cutout on the bottom for the nut. Refer to the CAD models if necessary.

The other side of the clamp has a tab on each piece: one with a hole and one with a slot. Using the tab with the hole, put your longer M3 bolt through the hole so that the bolt's head faces the other tab. Next, place the pen spring around the shank of the bolt, and secure it using an M3 nut. Holding that M3 nut in place, Add another M3 nut to the bolt, and torque the two nuts into each other to hold them in place. Push the bolt from the nuts towards the other tab so that the head of the bolt reaches just past the other tab. Move the bolt so that the shank of the bolt is inside of the slot in the other tab, and release the bolt. This will pull the two clamp halves together while allowing you to "stretch" the clamp open.

Finally, the mic insert is screwed into the clamp using the integrated threads. To mount your mic, first stretch the two elastic bands between opposite arms on the insert. The microphone sits between the two bands.

Oh, nothing fancy, just an analog square wave synthesizer...

That's OKAY!

  • Monophonic: Only one note at a time can be played. This is opposed to “polyphonic,” where multiple simultaneous notes can be played.
  • Analog: There are no computers, microcontrollers, sound samplers, or anything digital involved. The sound you hear is the sound of a speaker being abused by discrete electronic components like capacitors and resistors and logic chips.
  • Square-wave: When its output is viewed on an oscilloscope, its wave resembles a square. It’s a “hard” sounding wave type, great for bass lines, and commonly associated with chiptune music and old video games.

These are the 3D models for the OKAY DIY Kit. Read more about the project, its design, and where it's headed here.

Printing instructions

Slicing

I print everything at .2mm layer height by default.

To get multiple colors, insert color change GCODE at the recommended color change depth. (Assumes .2mm and allows extra room to minimize errant stringing problems, but you should verify in your slicing software before sending to printer.)

Assembly
  • Clean up strings
    • Cut or melt away any stringing. Be careful not to scratch dark filament underneath text embossing
  • Enclosure bottom
    • Break built-in bridge supports from each PCB post with a small screwdriver or other stabby object
  • Knobs
    • Cut built-in bridge support from bottom to expose shaft cavity
    • One knob has a hole in its side. This is a cavity for the brass threaded insert, which you’ll lock into place by inserting with a hot soldering iron

Final assembly information is available at http://blog.tommy.sh/posts/okay-synth and http://www.oskitone.com/guides
